Center: IAEA Nuclear Data Section, Vienna, Austria
title: Fission neutron spectrum averaged cross sections of some threshold reactions on tellurium: estimation of radioactive impurities in (n,g)-produced 131Te-131I

x4freetext: Fission neutron spectrum averaged cross sections of
some threshold reactions on tellurium: estimation
of radioactive impurities in (n,g)-produced 131Te-131I
University of the Punjab, Lahore, Pakistan
5 MW swimming pool type Pakistan
research reactor ( PARR-I) at Pinstech.
High purity tellurium oxide granules (99.999% pure),
weighing 25-50 mg, were filled in a quartz ampoule,
sealed and then placed in an NRX type irradiation
capsule. Two of each of the four neutron flux monitor
foils (Au, Co, Fe and Ni), were placed in a cylindrical
arrangement around the ampoule in such a way that the
same neutron flux monitor material was on opposite
sides of the ampoule, allowing thereby a determination
of the effective flux density within the ampoule.
The foils were washed with acetone; dried and weighed
before attaching to the ampoules.

x4codes.shortRef: Rept: I.A.E.A. technical report, Vienna, No.156, p.273 (1974)

x4freetext: First four monitor
reactions.
From measurement of the fast/thermal -neutron flux
ratio for monitor reactions having different threshold
it was concluded that the neutron spectrum used was
approximately a fission spectrum.
Cross sections were measured by neutron
activation of the target nuclei and the radioactive
products were identified by gamma-ray spectrometry.
A new radiochemical separation was proposed.
Tracer experiments showed the chemical yield of the
procedure up to 98 +- 2%.
The radioactivity of the reaction products and
the monitor reactions was determined by gamma-ray
spectrometry using a coaxial 30 cm3 Ge(Li) detector in
conjunction with a 4 K Canberra Series 85 multichannel
analyzer.
In converting the count rates to decay rates correc-
tions were applied for radiochemical yields, gamma-ray
intensities, detector efficiencies, counting geometry,
absorption, self-absorption, pile-up effects and
coincidence losses.
The reported uncertainties incorporate both
statistical and systematic errors. Main sources of
errors associated in cross-section measurements were
those associated with determination of fast neutron
flux densities (5%) and absolute decay rates (4 to 10%)
Other sources of error were small and were due to
uncertainties in the number of target nuclei < 1% and
in radiation and cooling times ( 1%).
Data taken from  Tabl.2 of main reference.
